gomodel:SYNGO_2231  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.2: \"Distribution and subcellular fractionation of GRIP1 and GRIP2 protein in brain\"\n- Literal: \"Treatment of synaptic plasma membrane fractions with various detergents to generate PSD fractions demonstrated that GRIP1 and GRIP2 were enriched in the PSD (Fig.2 e)\"\n\nFig.4: \"In vivo and in vitro interaction of full-length GRIP1 and AMPA receptors\"\nLiteral: \" These results demonstrate that GRIP1 and GRIP2 can associate with AMPA receptorsin situ in transfected cells and that GRIP1 is associated with AMPA receptors in vivo in brain\"\n\nFig.7: \"Immunogold electron microscopy localization of GRIP1 protein in CNS\"\n- Literal: \"Most frequently, the gold clusters appeared in dendrites (Fig. 7 b, arrows) and were typically associated with vesicles, sometimes clearly outlining a vesicular profile. These gold-labeled vesicles were often very close to microtubule filaments. Immunogold label was also found in postsynaptic spines, frequently near the PSD region (Fig. 7 c-e, arrows), and was occasionally found within the PSD (Fig. 7 c,arrows).\"\n\nI conclude from this data that when inside a synaptic region (synaptosomal preparation), Grip1 is preferentially localized in the PSD. However, the localization to undefined dendritic compartments may represent additional synapse-associated organelles involved in NTR trafficking.. Experimental description: \"To specifically examine the tissue distribution of GRIP1 and GRIP2, various rat tissues were analyzed by Western blot techniques using the GRIP1- and GRIP2-specific antibodies.\"\n\n\"Ultrastructral localization of GRIP1 in rat cortex and hippocampus\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-6153-3586" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2666-0758" ;
        dc:date           "2017-12-17" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_2231" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

